Example \(\PageIndex{7}\) Find the unknown side and angles of this triangle. Solution Notice that we don’t have both pieces of any side/angle pair, so the Law of Sines would not work with this triangle. Since we have the angle included between the two known sides, we can turn to Law of Cosines. Since the left side of any of the Law of Cosines equations involves the side opposite the known angle, the left side in this situation will involve the side x. The other two sides can be used in either order. \[{x^2} = {10^2} + {12^2} - 2(10)(12)\cos (30^\circ )
onumber\]Evaluate the cosine \[{x^2} = {10^2} + {12^2} - 2(10)(12)\dfrac{\sqrt 3 }{2}
onumber\]Simplify \[{x^2} = 244 - 120\sqrt 3 
onumber\]Take the square root \[x = \sqrt {244 - 120\sqrt 3 } \approx 6.013
onumber\] Now that we know an angle and its corresponding side, we can use the Law of Sines to fill in the remaining angles of the triangle. Solving for angle \(	heta\), \[\dfrac{\sin (30^\circ )}{6.013} = \dfrac{\sin (	heta )}{10}
onumber\] \[\sin (	heta ) = \dfrac{10\sin (30^\circ )}{6.013}
onumber\]Use the inverse sine \[	heta = {\sin ^{ - 1}}\left( \dfrac{10\sin (30^\circ )}{6.013} ight) \approx 56.256^\circ 
onumber\] The other possibility for \(	heta\) would be \(	heta = 180^{\circ} – 56.256^{\circ} = 123.744^{\circ}\). In the original picture, \(	heta\) is an acute angle, so 123.744°\(^{\circ}\) doesn’t make sense if we assume the picture is drawn to scale. Proceeding with \(	heta = 56.256^{\circ}\), we can then find the third angle of the triangle: \[\phi = 180^\circ - 30^\circ - 56.256^\circ = 93.744^\circ 
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{10}\) To measure the height of a hill, a woman measures the angle of elevation to the top of the hill to be 24 degrees. She then moves back 200 feet and measures the angle of elevation to be 22 degrees. Find the height of the hill. Solution As with many problems of this nature, it will be helpful to draw a picture. Notice there are three triangles formed here – the right triangle including the height \(h\) and the 22 degree angle, the right triangle including the height \(h\) and the 24 degree angle, and the (non-right) obtuse triangle including the 200 ft side. Since this is the triangle we have the most information for, we will begin with it. It may seem odd to work with this triangle since it does not include the desired side \(h\), but we don’t have enough information to work with either of the right triangles yet. We can find the obtuse angle of the triangle, since it and the angle of 24 degrees complete a straight line – a 180 degree angle. The obtuse angle must be \(180^{\circ} - 24^{\circ} = 156^{\circ}\). From this, we can determine that the third angle is \(2^{\circ}\). We know one side is 200 feet, and its corresponding angle is \(2^{\circ}\), so by introducing a temporary variable \(x\) for one of the other sides (as shown below), we can use Law of Sines to solve for this length \(x\). \[\dfrac{x}{\sin (22^\circ )} = \dfrac{200}{\sin (2^\circ )}
onumber\]Setting up the Law of Sines \[x = \sin (22^\circ )\dfrac{200}{\sin (2^\circ )}
onumber\]isolating the \(x\) value \[x = 2146.77	ext{ ft}
onumber\] Now that we know \(x\), we can use right triangle properties to solve for \(h\). \[\sin (24^\circ ) = \dfrac{m{opposite}}{m{hypotenuse}} = \dfrac{h}{x} = \dfrac{h}{2146.77}
onumber\] \[h = 2146.77\sin (24^\circ ) = 873.17	ext{ ft}
onumber\] The hill is 873 feet high.

